WEBVTT

00:00.960 --> 00:02.923
VERONICA:
<i>Previously on</i> Veronica Mars...

00:02.923 --> 00:06.262
Three spring breaks ago,
a Hearst Pi Sig dies on the beach.

00:06.262 --> 00:07.473
Written off as an accident.

00:07.473 --> 00:10.647
What can you tell me about
the night Patrick Hatcher died?

00:10.647 --> 00:12.651
‐ Get out! Now!

00:12.651 --> 00:14.655
‐ How are Murderheads
at deep background checks?

00:14.655 --> 00:16.575
‐ Deep background is where we excel.

00:16.575 --> 00:19.288
‐ Find out everything you can
about these three frat guys.

00:19.288 --> 00:20.374
‐ Consider it done.

00:20.374 --> 00:23.171
‐ I saw Eli's blonde crush
at the motel today.

00:23.171 --> 00:25.635
Pretty sure she was snooping around
Alonzo's room.

00:25.635 --> 00:27.973
‐ I'm gonna pay her a visit
at some point.

00:27.973 --> 00:29.308
KEITH:
I've been thinking a lot lately.

00:29.308 --> 00:32.691
I'm afraid that I'm just gonna end up
doing something s‐stupid.

00:32.691 --> 00:34.736
Or worse, get one of us hurt.

00:34.736 --> 00:36.615
‐ This is Logan. Yes, sir.

00:36.615 --> 00:38.786
I've been called back to active duty.
I need to leave immediately.

00:38.786 --> 00:40.289
LEO:
...is flippity‐flap. [ laughs ]

00:40.289 --> 00:41.457
KEITH: Have you noticed
that each of the bombs

00:41.457 --> 00:43.671
killed someone
with a sex offense in his history?

00:43.671 --> 00:46.009
It's a pattern. But I was missing a perp.

00:46.009 --> 00:47.637
What about Nicole?
‐ You ready?

00:50.852 --> 00:53.774
‐ It's your lucky day, Congressman.
You get to meet Allah.

00:55.737 --> 00:58.199
‐ Daniel!
‐ Neptune Grand, eighth floor.

00:58.199 --> 01:00.037
AMALIA: Daniel...

01:06.257 --> 01:09.138
‐ <i>[ police radio chatter ]</i>

01:09.138 --> 01:11.894
‐ [ sighs ] Say that again?

01:12.771 --> 01:15.025
‐ Those two, Dodie Mendoza

01:15.025 --> 01:18.281
and Alonzo Lozano,
were paid 30 Bitcoin,

01:18.281 --> 01:21.997
which is $100,000 more or less,
by Congressman Maloof.

01:21.997 --> 01:24.377
KEITH: And a source of ours
spotted driver's licenses

01:24.377 --> 01:27.759
for Tayler and Tyler Carr
in those boys' motel room.

01:27.759 --> 01:29.011
It's that‐‐ that page right there.

01:29.011 --> 01:30.222
‐ Enough.

01:30.222 --> 01:31.474
All right.

01:32.101 --> 01:33.771
Here's how this went down.

01:33.771 --> 01:36.484
Tyler Carr shot Daniel Maloof

01:36.484 --> 01:38.488
over a missing ring.

01:38.488 --> 01:40.910
Hell, I witnessed them
nearly come to blows over it

01:40.910 --> 01:42.539
in the coroner's office.

01:42.539 --> 01:45.043
You were there.
Are you forgetting this?

01:45.043 --> 01:47.757
‐ King Pagursky's mom is on line two.

01:47.757 --> 01:49.719
‐ [ Marcia sighs ]

01:53.017 --> 01:55.439
MARCIA: Mrs. Pagursky.
MRS. PAGURSKY: <i>Are you avoiding my calls?</i>

01:55.439 --> 01:59.531
‐ No, ma'am. No.
Ma'am, we are invested in making sure

01:59.531 --> 02:01.200
that you get a positive result
to this case.

02:01.200 --> 02:02.745
MRS. PAGURSKY: <i>Well, it doesn't seem like</i>
<i>things are moving fast enough‐‐</i>

02:02.745 --> 02:03.163
‐ [ sighs ]

02:03.163 --> 02:05.167
<i>[ soft music playing ]</i>

02:05.167 --> 02:05.710
<i>[ Pony whines ]</i>

02:05.710 --> 02:07.755
‐ Ohh! Drool on the dirty laundry,

02:07.755 --> 02:09.759
not the clean laundry!

02:09.759 --> 02:11.345
<i>[ laptop chiming ]</i>

02:11.345 --> 02:13.433
Oh, shit!

02:16.105 --> 02:17.274
Hi, babe!

02:17.274 --> 02:19.571
Here, talk to Pony. I need one sec.

02:21.491 --> 02:22.702
‐ <i>Hi, Pony!</i>

02:22.702 --> 02:24.664
[ Pony groans ]

02:24.664 --> 02:27.921
<i>Good talk. Veronica!</i>

02:30.300 --> 02:31.512
‐ Hi!

02:31.512 --> 02:33.097
‐ <i>Did you move the car</i>
<i>for street cleaning?</i>

02:33.097 --> 02:34.099
‐ Shit.

02:35.895 --> 02:37.732
[ paper bag rustling ]

02:37.732 --> 02:40.278
DODIE: She's gonna get a ticket
if she doesn't move her car soon.

02:41.197 --> 02:43.243
ALONZO: Maybe you should knock
on her door and let her know.

02:46.834 --> 02:50.215
You notice all the fast food places here
use paper straws?

02:50.215 --> 02:52.177
You know, because of the sea turtles.

02:53.388 --> 02:55.852
DODIE:
We should have followed the father.

02:56.770 --> 02:59.275
‐ So you could bitch about how
we should have followed the daughter?

02:59.275 --> 03:00.862
Just be where you are.

03:00.862 --> 03:03.491
‐ We should kill 'em
and be done with it.

03:03.491 --> 03:07.750
‐ We can do that, keep tryin'
to find the bomber on our own.

03:07.750 --> 03:11.007
Or we could wait for the professional
private investigators

03:11.007 --> 03:13.052
to track down the bomber <i>for</i> us.

03:13.052 --> 03:14.806
And then kill 'em.

03:17.311 --> 03:19.231
[ slurps ]

03:19.231 --> 03:21.277
<i>[ theme music playing ]</i>

03:21.277 --> 03:23.657
SINGER:
<i>♪ A long time ago ♪</i>

03:23.657 --> 03:25.452
<i>♪ We used to be friends ♪</i>

03:25.452 --> 03:30.128
<i>♪ But I haven't thought of you</i>
<i>lately at all ♪</i>

03:31.923 --> 03:33.886
<i>♪ Bring it on, bring it on, yeah ♪</i>

03:33.886 --> 03:36.516
<i>♪ Just remember me when ♪</i>

03:36.516 --> 03:38.854
<i>♪ We used to be friends ♪</i>

03:40.190 --> 03:42.987
<i>♪ A long time ago ♪</i>

03:42.987 --> 03:45.408
<i>♪ We used to be friends ♪</i>

03:45.408 --> 03:47.830
<i>♪ A long time ago ♪</i>

03:47.830 --> 03:50.251
<i>♪ We used to be friends ♪</i>

03:50.251 --> 03:51.505
<i>♪ Hey ♪</i>

03:55.261 --> 03:57.725
VERONICA: I'm glad you called,
but I'm leaving soon.

03:57.725 --> 04:00.355
Uh, Wallace should be here in...

04:00.355 --> 04:01.942
[ knocking on door ]

04:01.942 --> 04:04.446
...five minutes early, like a dick.

04:04.446 --> 04:06.827
How's, uh, parts unknown?

04:06.827 --> 04:09.582
‐ <i>Well, I had to wait 45 minutes</i>
<i>for this Skype session,</i>

04:09.582 --> 04:12.588
<i>but other than that,</i>
<i>it's all lollipops and rainbows.</i>

04:14.007 --> 04:15.427
‐ Hi.
‐ Hi. I just need two secs.

04:15.427 --> 04:16.470
Talk to Wallace.

04:17.849 --> 04:18.851
‐ What's up, Logan?

04:18.851 --> 04:21.355
LOGAN: <i>[ laughs ]</i>
<i>What's up, Wallace?</i>

04:21.355 --> 04:24.278
‐ Well, the district offered me
the varsity coaching job.

04:24.278 --> 04:26.032
LOGAN:
<i>That's great!</i>

04:26.700 --> 04:29.246
‐ It's at Kane High.
LOGAN: <i>Sheesh. Does Veronica know?</i>

04:29.246 --> 04:31.877
‐ I'm afraid to tell her.
LOGAN: <i>Yeah, I don't blame you.</i>

04:32.712 --> 04:33.839
‐ Turn it towards me.

04:35.551 --> 04:37.012
Sorry, we're just running late.

04:37.012 --> 04:39.183
‐ Well, movie's not for half an hour.

04:39.183 --> 04:42.189
‐ Actually...
‐ Oh, Veronica.

04:42.189 --> 04:46.280
‐ I was hoping you could come
do a thing with me before the movie.

04:46.280 --> 04:48.660
‐ Before the movie
or in place of the movie?

04:48.660 --> 04:51.290
‐ Uh, in place of the 8:00 movie,

04:51.290 --> 04:55.048
but <i>before</i> the 10:00 movie
I was hoping we could go to instead.

04:55.048 --> 04:58.262
It's just a quick Murderheads meeting.
You'll barely know we're there.

04:58.262 --> 04:59.933
‐ <i>You seem busy.</i>

04:59.933 --> 05:01.603
<i>I'll try you tomorrow.</i>

05:02.354 --> 05:04.483
‐ [ sighs ] I'm sorry.

05:04.483 --> 05:06.403
If I knew you were calling, I‐‐

05:06.403 --> 05:09.493
‐ <i>Not exactly on a set schedule here,</i>
<i>Veronica.</i>

05:09.493 --> 05:11.288
‐ Doesn't mean I don't have one.

05:11.288 --> 05:13.000
‐ <i>I know that.</i>

05:13.000 --> 05:17.259
‐ I can't just wait in front
of the computer, hoping.

05:17.259 --> 05:18.804
LOGAN: <i>I wouldn't expect you to.</i>

05:19.429 --> 05:22.477
<i>But... have a good night.</i>

05:22.477 --> 05:23.271
‐ Logan‐‐

05:23.271 --> 05:24.607
<i>[ sign‐off sound ]</i>

05:24.607 --> 05:26.152
[ sighs ]

05:27.530 --> 05:30.493
‐ So... <i>what</i> is a Murderhead?

05:31.538 --> 05:34.878
‐ Hearst student
and Pi Sig president Campbell Davis

05:34.878 --> 05:36.255
got a DUI last month.

05:36.255 --> 05:38.176
He's on academic probation,

05:38.176 --> 05:40.806
and his pledge name was "Jizz Mop."

05:40.806 --> 05:42.142
DON:
<i>God, I miss Hearst.</i>

05:44.062 --> 05:46.192
‐ Anything that relates
to the beach party

05:46.192 --> 05:49.616
where his fellow
Pi Sig pledge Patrick Hatcher died

05:49.616 --> 05:51.327
three spring breaks ago?

05:51.327 --> 05:54.834
‐ He posted an "R.I.P." shout‐out to him
on Facebook, but that's it.

05:54.834 --> 05:57.130
‐ What about Darren Silva?

05:57.130 --> 05:59.969
‐ He was pretty active on social media‐‐
the standard stuff‐‐

05:59.969 --> 06:02.015
until the night Hatcher died.

06:02.015 --> 06:04.436
After that, radio silence.

06:04.436 --> 06:07.652
‐ Not even one tweet saying,
"What happened that night

06:07.652 --> 06:10.448
makes me want to murder
future spring breakers"?

06:10.448 --> 06:12.077
DON:
<i>[ laughs ] Hey,</i>

06:12.077 --> 06:15.584
<i>if the desire to murder spring breakers</i>
<i>is wrong, I don't wanna be right.</i>

06:15.584 --> 06:17.170
CAROL:
Ugh. Don!

06:17.170 --> 06:20.385
‐ <i>Oh, lighten up. Everyone who's ever</i>
<i>lived in Neptune has thought it.</i>

06:20.385 --> 06:21.805
‐ Yeah, I've thought it.

06:24.101 --> 06:25.980
Damn, did I say that out loud?

06:25.980 --> 06:28.902
For the record,
I'm not the murderer. I'm‐‐

06:28.902 --> 06:30.280
PENN:
Okay. Moving on

06:30.280 --> 06:32.158
to Blake Long,
which... we didn't find much.

06:32.158 --> 06:33.912
He changed his major sophomore year

06:33.912 --> 06:37.837
and then started a band
called Suit Slayer.

06:38.588 --> 06:40.466
‐ "Soothsayer."

06:40.466 --> 06:42.930
PENN:
Soothsayer, that's right.

06:42.930 --> 06:45.435
‐ Both equally unhelpful.

06:45.435 --> 06:47.355
DON:
<i>Sorry, guys, I gotta jump.</i>

06:47.355 --> 06:49.484
<i>I'm briefing Pelosi in 20.</i>

06:49.484 --> 06:50.779
‐ Looking like that?

06:50.779 --> 06:54.077
‐ <i>Well, when you're</i> the <i>guy</i>
<i>on international debt relief,</i>

06:54.077 --> 06:55.664
<i>you dress how you like.</i>

06:55.664 --> 06:56.958
<i>Peace out, murder scouts.</i>

06:57.918 --> 07:00.298
‐ Um, does anybody
have anything else?

07:00.298 --> 07:04.056
‐ Yeah. Blake Long tried to kill himself
a month after Hatcher died in that fire.

07:04.056 --> 07:07.228
‐ Long did? I thought you were
doing Darren Silva.

07:07.228 --> 07:10.068
‐ Adderall. I can go all night.

07:10.068 --> 07:13.575
[ banging, clattering ]

07:17.750 --> 07:19.127
[ slams cabinet door ]

07:20.379 --> 07:21.716
‐ We're out of sugar.

07:21.716 --> 07:24.889
‐ God, I love having you
around the office.

07:24.889 --> 07:28.062
That contagious smile,
that youthful enthusiasm.

07:28.062 --> 07:31.443
How many people get to work
with an actual ray of sunshine?

07:33.364 --> 07:36.453
‐ I've been listening to the bug
I planted in Nicole's office,

07:36.453 --> 07:38.542
and I hate myself.

07:39.209 --> 07:40.546
‐ So stop listening.

07:41.798 --> 07:44.554
‐ Stop listening?
Is that possible?

07:44.554 --> 07:46.098
‐ If you're sure about her,

07:46.098 --> 07:49.104
the next time you're at the bar
just take back the bug

07:49.104 --> 07:51.693
and just go on having your, uh,

07:51.693 --> 07:54.406
whatever the female version
of a bromance is.

07:54.406 --> 07:55.576
‐ A friendship?

07:55.576 --> 07:57.078
‐ A friendship. That's it.

07:58.247 --> 07:59.834
It's your call, honey.

08:23.047 --> 08:24.382
‐ [ sighs ]

08:24.382 --> 08:25.594
BARTENDER [ on recording ]:
<i>He's a nice kid.</i>

08:25.594 --> 08:27.932
NICOLE: <i>Who breaks a glass in the ice</i>
<i>every 15 minutes.</i>

08:27.932 --> 08:29.184
<i>He needs to get himself a retail job.</i>

08:29.184 --> 08:29.602
<i>[ beep ]</i>

08:29.602 --> 08:31.814
<i>I only need three cases this week.</i>

08:31.814 --> 08:33.735
<i>Business is slow, man.</i>

08:33.735 --> 08:34.277
<i>[ beep ]</i>

08:34.277 --> 08:37.325
<i>Just open the box and pour the pizza</i>
<i>directly down my throat.</i>

08:37.325 --> 08:39.830
PENN: <i>I know it's a bad day</i>
<i>when you order extra cheese.</i>

08:39.830 --> 08:41.834
NICOLE: <i>And when you're here</i>
<i>more than once a week.</i>

08:41.834 --> 08:43.838
PENN:
<i>Must be nice, getting to relax.</i>

08:43.838 --> 08:46.009
NICOLE:
<i>If I didn't care about making money.</i>

08:46.009 --> 08:47.805
PENN: <i>Hey,</i>
<i>if he woulda left Quacks alone,</i>

08:47.805 --> 08:50.142
<i>I might have started</i>
<i>a Neptune Bomber fan club.</i>

08:50.142 --> 08:51.604
<i>They're heathens. I won't miss 'em.</i>

08:51.604 --> 08:52.898
[ stops recording ]

08:52.898 --> 08:56.656
‐ Sounds like Nicole orders pizza
from Penn all the time.

08:56.656 --> 09:00.162
‐ Oh, you've done it, Veronica.
You've cracked this thing wide open.

09:00.162 --> 09:03.210
‐ I'm spitballin' here! No bad ideas.

09:03.210 --> 09:05.757
I'm throwin' stuff at the wall,
seein' what sticks.

09:05.757 --> 09:10.809
What if Penn delivered a pizza
to Quacks on the day of the bombing,

09:10.809 --> 09:15.736
he's got one of those pizza delivery bags,
he slides into the men's room... okay...

09:17.405 --> 09:19.702
[ sighs ] Sorry.
I'm getting carried away.

09:19.702 --> 09:20.746
‐ Maybe not.

09:22.165 --> 09:24.670
I mean, it's thin,
but Chattanooga Charlie's,

09:24.670 --> 09:26.549
where they had the explosion
last spring break,

09:26.549 --> 09:28.511
Cho's delivers there, too.

09:28.511 --> 09:31.308
Maybe the squirrely cuss made a mistake
with the first bomb.

09:31.308 --> 09:34.732
He delivered the pizza to the Sea Sprite
and didn't get out in time.

09:35.942 --> 09:37.738
What's his motive?

09:38.948 --> 09:40.661
‐ Uh...

09:40.661 --> 09:43.290
he calls spring breakers "heathens"
on the recording.

09:43.290 --> 09:45.545
‐ They are heathens.
We've called them worse.

09:45.545 --> 09:47.090
‐ Much worse.

09:47.090 --> 09:49.427
So I should find out from Nicole

09:49.427 --> 09:53.728
if Penn delivered her a pizza
at Comrade Quacks the day of the bombing.

09:53.728 --> 09:57.653
‐ How ya gonna do that without giving up
that you had a bug in her office?

09:57.653 --> 09:59.865
‐ Lie.

10:02.663 --> 10:06.294
VERONICA: <i>Do character flaws count less</i>
<i>if you're self‐aware about them?</i>

10:06.294 --> 10:08.465
<i>I went out with a guy for a while</i>
<i>at Columbia</i>

10:08.465 --> 10:10.846
<i>who was up front about his jealousy.</i>

10:10.846 --> 10:13.935
<i>He knew it was wrong,</i>
<i>apologized for it.</i>

10:13.935 --> 10:16.691
<i>But he was still the asshole</i>
<i>who wanted the gory details</i>

10:16.691 --> 10:18.862
<i>about every guy I'd ever touched.</i>

10:18.862 --> 10:21.450
<i>His self‐awareness didn't stop me</i>
<i>from dropping him.</i>

10:21.450 --> 10:21.868
[ door opens ]

10:21.868 --> 10:23.287
NICOLE:
Greg said you were up here.

10:23.287 --> 10:25.625
I've been thinking about you.

10:25.625 --> 10:27.588
VERONICA: Yeah?
‐ Uh‐huh.

10:27.588 --> 10:31.763
You and Leo the other night
seemed very friendly.

10:31.763 --> 10:34.894
And then he walked you <i>home.</i>
I mean, look,

10:34.894 --> 10:38.025
I've done some bad shit,
so no judgment, okay?

10:38.025 --> 10:39.904
I get it.
‐ Leo is just a friend.

10:39.904 --> 10:42.743
‐ Well, we're friends, right?
‐ Yeah. I hope so.

10:42.743 --> 10:45.247
‐ Yeah, well, the beauty
of being friends with me

10:45.247 --> 10:47.961
is that whatever you've done,
I've done something worse.

10:47.961 --> 10:50.592
‐ [ laughs ]

10:50.592 --> 10:53.013
Scout's honor, nothing happened.
‐ Hm.

10:53.013 --> 10:55.059
‐ Um... strange question.

10:55.059 --> 10:57.438
The day the bomb went off here,

10:57.438 --> 10:59.317
did you order pizza from Cho's?

10:59.317 --> 11:01.572
‐ That <i>is</i> a strange question.

11:01.572 --> 11:05.329
‐ It's probably nothing,
but I'm just wondering if the bomber

11:05.329 --> 11:08.878
is someone who gets in and out of places
like a pizza guy,

11:08.878 --> 11:11.132
someone who no one thinks about.

11:11.132 --> 11:15.391
‐ Well, I do order from Cho's
more than I should, but...

11:15.391 --> 11:18.230
I don't remember if I did
the day the bomb went off.

11:18.230 --> 11:20.109
It's kind of a blur.

11:20.109 --> 11:23.407
‐ Maybe you could check the receipts?
‐ Yeah. Sure.

11:24.827 --> 11:28.125
Okay, random question for you.
How do you feel about mud baths?

11:29.043 --> 11:31.966
‐ Uh...
support them for pigs.

11:31.966 --> 11:35.682
‐ Okay. So I just heard about
this new spa in Ojai,

11:35.682 --> 11:38.813
and I was thinking we should maybe
check it out after spring break.

11:38.813 --> 11:42.486
You know, we'll just, like,
get all the alcohol out of our pores

11:42.486 --> 11:44.783
and reset our fine selves.

11:47.831 --> 11:49.125
Veronica.

11:50.587 --> 11:53.551
‐ I planted a bug in your office.

11:55.513 --> 11:57.308
‐ What?

11:57.308 --> 12:00.189
‐ In every bomb,
at least one of the victims

12:00.189 --> 12:03.362
had some sort of sexual offense
on his record, and came through Quacks.

12:03.362 --> 12:06.451
I saw you knock
that kid Jimmy Hatfield out

12:06.451 --> 12:07.746
in the surveillance video,

12:07.746 --> 12:10.877
and the horse collar bomber
was in here trying to roofie girls.

12:10.877 --> 12:14.133
I mean, you own sap gloves.
for Chrissakes.

12:14.133 --> 12:17.264
The sex crime element
gave you motive.

12:17.264 --> 12:19.812
When a bomb went off in here,
I figured you'd never bomb your own place,

12:19.812 --> 12:21.398
but then I learned
you sold out to Big Dick‐‐

12:21.398 --> 12:22.859
‐ Stop!

12:24.404 --> 12:26.116
You've been <i>listening</i> to me.

12:31.292 --> 12:34.382
Where did you put it? The bug.

12:34.382 --> 12:37.013
‐ Um...

12:37.013 --> 12:38.516
there.

12:40.979 --> 12:42.941
‐ [ laughs softly ]

12:42.941 --> 12:45.237
So...

12:45.237 --> 12:48.786
I shared my deepest, darkest
personal secret,

12:48.786 --> 12:52.334
and your response
was to bug my office.

12:52.334 --> 12:55.340
I mean‐‐ I mean,
you really think I'm capable

12:55.340 --> 12:57.846
of randomly killing
a bunch of college kids.

12:57.846 --> 12:58.848
[ stammers ]

12:58.848 --> 13:01.311
But yet you still consider me a friend.
I mean‐‐

13:01.311 --> 13:04.192
Shit, Veronica,
how low is the bar for you?

13:04.192 --> 13:07.364
‐ I didn't really think you did it‐‐

13:07.364 --> 13:10.955
it‐‐ it's just part of the job.

13:10.955 --> 13:14.880
And I'm telling you because
I don't want this between us anymore.

13:17.301 --> 13:20.099
‐ Oh, so you feel better now, yeah?
You good?

13:22.311 --> 13:24.065
‐ Um, no.

13:26.444 --> 13:28.574
‐ Well, you've gotten close to me.

13:28.574 --> 13:30.537
You know me.

13:30.537 --> 13:33.291
How do you think I feel about
giving people second chances?

13:36.381 --> 13:39.262
‐ You've always done something worse,
right?

13:39.262 --> 13:41.349
‐ No.

13:41.349 --> 13:42.936
Not in this case.

13:46.150 --> 13:47.988
Is the bug still here?

13:52.413 --> 13:54.083
Then what are you waitin' for?

13:56.004 --> 13:57.214
<i>Go.</i>

14:02.809 --> 14:04.270
‐ [ Veronica sighs ]

14:07.903 --> 14:09.948
<i>[ pop music playing ]</i>

14:09.948 --> 14:12.036
<i>[ phone chiming ]</i>

14:14.165 --> 14:16.545
‐ [ sighs ] This is Veronica.

14:18.883 --> 14:21.931
I don't know why
she's not calling you back.

14:21.931 --> 14:24.937
Yes, she is staying with me.
She's just not... here right now.

14:26.523 --> 14:29.153
Look, I'll have her call you, okay?

14:35.792 --> 14:38.171
It learns.
‐ Sometimes.

14:39.716 --> 14:43.516
‐ Next up is phone etiquette.
‐ Did you call?

14:43.516 --> 14:45.812
‐ I did. So did your mom.

14:45.812 --> 14:49.903
‐ Shit. I've been turning my phone off
to conserve battery.

14:49.903 --> 14:51.865
‐ But you have internet?

14:51.865 --> 14:55.247
‐ I steal Wi‐Fi from a café
across the street.

14:55.247 --> 14:57.292
I'm just sending her a text.

14:59.171 --> 15:03.304
‐ So what does one do
in a motel room with no electricity?

15:03.304 --> 15:06.979
‐ Eat. Sleep.
Entertain revenge fantasies.

15:17.207 --> 15:18.418
‐ What?

15:21.800 --> 15:24.556
‐ This nail from Comrade Quacks,

15:24.556 --> 15:27.478
this nail removed from Penn's back,

15:27.478 --> 15:30.150
and this string art nail
are all the same.

15:30.150 --> 15:32.279
Does that strike you as strange?

15:32.279 --> 15:33.532
‐ No.

15:33.532 --> 15:35.202
‐ It should.

15:37.164 --> 15:38.416
Answer your phone.

15:46.099 --> 15:48.436
‐ [ indistinct chatter ]

15:50.190 --> 15:51.484
‐ This nail.

15:51.484 --> 15:54.574
It's the same as the ones
we looked for at the hardware store.

15:54.574 --> 15:59.041
It's the same as the one I found
in Comrade Quacks after the bombing.

15:59.041 --> 16:02.339
‐ Was the "hello" implied, or we're just,
we're not doin' that anymore?

16:03.007 --> 16:04.553
‐ Were they in every bomb?

16:06.640 --> 16:08.686
‐ No. Just the last three.

16:08.686 --> 16:11.274
The beach, the horse collar,
and Quacks.

16:12.569 --> 16:16.200
‐ So the bomb at the Sea Sprite
and the bomb that killed Perry Walsh

16:16.200 --> 16:17.745
were not packed with nails?

16:17.745 --> 16:21.712
‐ Right. Veronica, um...
what's up?

16:23.339 --> 16:24.885
‐ I'm working on something.

16:24.885 --> 16:27.472
If it amounts to anything,
I'll let you know.

16:27.472 --> 16:29.310
That's a cinnamon roll, by the way.

16:29.310 --> 16:30.938
‐ Aw.
‐ Enjoy.

16:36.575 --> 16:38.787
‐ Hey, uh...

16:38.787 --> 16:42.044
so as luck would have it,
they're playing <i>The Big Lebowski</i>

16:42.044 --> 16:44.089
at the Orpheus tonight.

16:44.089 --> 16:46.260
I'm ready to right this wrong if you are.

16:47.137 --> 16:49.141
‐ Why would I watch it
at that moldy dump

16:49.141 --> 16:50.686
when I have the director's cut

16:50.686 --> 16:53.567
and the ingredients for White Russians
at home?

16:53.567 --> 16:55.696
‐ Sold. What time should I be there?

16:56.657 --> 16:58.076
‐ That wasn't an invitation.

16:58.076 --> 16:59.411
‐ Ooh. Sounded like one.

16:59.411 --> 17:02.752
‐ You are not coming over
to Lebowski and chill.

17:02.752 --> 17:04.673
‐ You're turning this
into something tawdry.

17:04.673 --> 17:07.386
Ah, what's wrong with
a couple of cinephiles

17:07.386 --> 17:10.016
watching what you consider
to be a classic movie?

17:11.352 --> 17:13.439
Unless...

17:13.439 --> 17:15.193
unless you were thinking
it was something more.

17:17.322 --> 17:18.701
‐ I wasn't.

17:18.701 --> 17:21.330
‐ You afraid of being alone with me?

17:21.330 --> 17:22.875
‐ I'm leaving now.

17:22.875 --> 17:25.088
‐ Okay, so, is that‐‐
is that a yes or a no on me comin' over?

17:25.088 --> 17:28.512
‐ It was a "no invitation
has ever been issued."

17:28.512 --> 17:31.768
‐ You sure? Uh, can the court reporter
please play back the transcript

17:31.768 --> 17:34.398
starting with the part
about owning the movie in question

17:34.398 --> 17:37.822
and having the cocktail ingredients
at home?

17:37.822 --> 17:39.116
Goodbye.

17:48.677 --> 17:50.681
<i>[ rock music playing on car radio ]</i>

17:57.444 --> 17:58.864
[ turns off engine ]

17:58.864 --> 18:01.745
BIG DICK:
Hey, Clyde. Have you seen these bikes?

18:01.745 --> 18:05.293
This one has 4,000 cycling classes on it.
It's incredible!

18:05.293 --> 18:07.590
TRAINER [ on video ]: <i>Nice work!</i>
‐ I just got the countersigned contracts

18:07.590 --> 18:09.009
for Comrade Quacks.
‐ Mm‐hm.

18:09.009 --> 18:10.596
‐ You're leasin' it to Rick Deefenbock?

18:10.596 --> 18:13.142
‐ Damn right.
The dumb son of a bitch overpaid.

18:13.142 --> 18:15.355
‐ That was supposed to be
my property, Dick.

18:15.355 --> 18:19.238
TRAINER: <i>Thirty seconds to go!</i>
‐ We talked about this. At length.

18:20.574 --> 18:23.413
‐ Oh, right.
Your "classic car" dealership?

18:23.413 --> 18:25.793
Comrade Quacks, that's where
you wanted to put it? You sure?

18:25.793 --> 18:27.547
‐ Positive.
TRAINER: <i>Go strong here!</i>

18:27.547 --> 18:29.843
‐ Oh, I'm sorry, buddy.
It must have slipped my mind.

18:29.843 --> 18:32.807
But don't worry,
we'll find you another lot.

18:32.807 --> 18:35.646
A better lot.
If that's still what you want.

18:35.646 --> 18:37.274
‐ Why would that not be what I want?

18:37.274 --> 18:39.361
‐ Well, owning a business,
especially one that trades

18:39.361 --> 18:41.742
in a rarified secondary market
with little practical demand

18:41.742 --> 18:43.327
and a shrinking consumer base...

18:43.327 --> 18:45.248
not exactly the venture
to cut your teeth on.

18:46.543 --> 18:48.547
‐ Yeah, well, that was our deal.

18:48.547 --> 18:50.801
‐ And what was our deal exactly?
What was the language?

18:50.801 --> 18:53.097
TRAINER: <i>You've got this!</i>
‐ You gave me your word.

18:53.097 --> 18:54.517
‐ You're still learning.
What's the rush?

18:54.517 --> 18:58.232
‐ Spent a decade of my life in prison,
I'd kinda like to not waste any more time.

18:58.232 --> 19:00.111
‐ Well, won't be long.
We'll find you something.

19:00.111 --> 19:02.282
TRAINER: <i>Another 15!</i>
‐ Hey.

19:02.282 --> 19:04.996
What's a dream car for a teenage girl?
You know what? I don't ever care.

19:04.996 --> 19:07.752
Just pick one and find out where
the girl from the Sea Sprite is.

19:07.752 --> 19:09.839
Will ya? But it's gotta be red.

19:09.839 --> 19:11.258
Girls love red.

19:11.258 --> 19:12.595
‐ Sure thing.
TRAINER: <i>Just up the hill!</i>

19:12.595 --> 19:14.139
‐ My man.

19:14.139 --> 19:16.561
Shit, another hill.
[ grunts ]

19:16.561 --> 19:18.397
TRAINER:
<i>You can do it! Let's go!</i>

19:23.659 --> 19:26.623
‐ I know why we've been
having such a tough time with his case.

19:26.623 --> 19:28.627
These nails‐‐

19:28.627 --> 19:30.463
[ sniffs ]

19:32.008 --> 19:33.762
Where is it?

19:34.973 --> 19:36.308
‐ Where's what?

19:41.820 --> 19:43.740
Personal space! Personal space!

19:43.740 --> 19:47.748
‐ [ gasps ] A milkshake,
a Lumberjack Timber‐gur,

19:47.748 --> 19:49.669
<i>and</i> waffle fries.

19:49.669 --> 19:52.090
Well, well, well.

19:52.090 --> 19:57.142
When this cat's away, the mouse‐‐
that's you‐‐ will consume 2,000 calories.

19:57.142 --> 20:00.566
‐ But, Veronica,
I'm a lumberjack and I'm okay.

20:00.566 --> 20:02.152
‐ Don't be cute with me.

20:02.152 --> 20:04.323
‐ You were gonna tell me
something about nails?

20:04.323 --> 20:07.788
‐ Fine. I'll try to fill you in
before your inevitable heart attack.

20:09.834 --> 20:11.546
This nail.

20:11.546 --> 20:15.386
It's the same type of nail
that was removed from Penn's back.

20:15.386 --> 20:18.309
It's also the type of nail
that was used as shrapnel

20:18.309 --> 20:21.858
in the beach bomb, the Quacks bomb,
and the horse collar bomb.

20:21.858 --> 20:23.444
‐ And the Sea Sprite bomb.

20:24.697 --> 20:26.116
‐ What makes you say that?

20:26.116 --> 20:28.789
‐ Because it was pulled out
of Penn's back.

20:28.789 --> 20:32.797
‐ Yeah, but the only person hit
with this type of nail <i>was</i> Penn.

20:32.797 --> 20:38.224
Leo confirmed that the first two bombs
weren't packed with these nails.

20:38.224 --> 20:41.313
This is also the same kind of nail
that's used in string art.

20:41.313 --> 20:43.275
I saw the piece in Matty's room.

20:43.275 --> 20:46.323
It was hanging on the wall
inside the office

20:46.323 --> 20:49.622
just a few feet
from where Penn was outside.

20:49.622 --> 20:52.085
‐ So you're saying Penn
gets a few of these nails in his back

20:52.085 --> 20:53.797
and makes the incorrect assumption

20:53.797 --> 20:56.553
that the bombs are loaded
with these nails as shrapnel.

20:56.553 --> 21:01.061
‐ Then when his theory that the Maloofs
were trying to kill their future in‐law

21:01.061 --> 21:04.276
is shot out of the water
and he becomes a laughingstock...

21:04.276 --> 21:05.946
‐ He takes over for Perry Walsh,

21:05.946 --> 21:08.492
using what he believes is Walsh's M. O.

21:08.492 --> 21:12.042
‐ Then he stands up at a City Council
meeting and blames Big Dick

21:12.042 --> 21:15.549
because he knows
we think it's Big Dick.

21:15.549 --> 21:18.012
‐ But Penn wasn't the only one
who knew about the nails.

21:18.012 --> 21:19.807
The Murderheads knew.
The police know.

21:20.809 --> 21:22.437
‐ If there are two bombers,

21:22.437 --> 21:25.234
everything we thought about Big Dick
works out.

21:25.234 --> 21:28.909
‐ Big Dick gets his prison library buddy
Perry Walsh to bomb the Sea Sprite.

21:28.909 --> 21:31.121
It's a location he wants to buy,

21:31.121 --> 21:33.835
and the owner is starting
to organize merchants against him.

21:33.835 --> 21:37.635
He then eliminates Walsh,
making it look like he killed himself,

21:37.635 --> 21:41.016
even provides
a "I hate girls in bikinis" manifesto.

21:41.016 --> 21:43.312
‐ And then Penn takes over.

21:46.318 --> 21:48.824
‐ Let's call the chief of police,
see what she says.

21:48.824 --> 21:50.368
‐ She's not gonna listen.

21:50.368 --> 21:51.871
‐ Probably not.

21:51.871 --> 21:53.708
<i>[ dial tone ]</i>

21:53.708 --> 21:56.548
‐ I'm gonna let you enjoy this experience
on your own.

21:56.548 --> 22:00.514
Good night. Oh, and if you feel
a tightness in your chest

22:00.514 --> 22:02.935
and break out in a cold sweat,
just remember:

22:02.935 --> 22:05.899
Put. The burger. Down.

22:05.899 --> 22:07.778
‐ Chief. It's Keith Mars,

22:07.778 --> 22:09.782
says he has a theory
he wants to run by you.

22:09.782 --> 22:10.951
‐ [ scoffs ]

22:10.951 --> 22:13.080
Tell him to piss up a rope.

22:15.251 --> 22:17.046
[ knocking on door ]

22:49.612 --> 22:51.448
FEMALE SINGER:
<i>♪ What do you want from me? ♪</i>

22:51.448 --> 22:53.369
<i>♪ Why don't you run from me?</i>

22:53.369 --> 22:55.540
<i>♪ What are you wondering? ♪</i>

22:55.540 --> 22:56.668
<i>♪ What do you know? ♪</i>

22:56.668 --> 22:57.753
MALE SINGER:
<i>♪ Come here ♪</i>

22:57.753 --> 22:59.757
FEMALE SINGER:
<i>♪ Say it, spit it out ♪</i>

23:00.509 --> 23:02.846
<i>♪ What is it exactly you're payin'? ♪</i>

23:02.846 --> 23:05.978
<i>♪ Is the amount cleaning you out,</i>
<i>am I satisfactory? ♪</i>

23:05.978 --> 23:10.027
<i>♪ Today I'm thinkin' about</i>
<i>the things that are deadly ♪</i>

23:10.027 --> 23:12.490
<i>♪ The way I'm drinkin' you down,</i>
<i>like I wanna drown ♪</i>

23:12.490 --> 23:14.077
<i>♪ Like I wanna end me ♪</i>

23:14.077 --> 23:15.747
<i>♪ Step on the glass ♪</i>

23:15.747 --> 23:17.835
<i>♪ Staple your tongue, ahh ♪</i>

23:17.835 --> 23:19.462
<i>♪ Bury a friend ♪</i>

23:19.462 --> 23:22.176
<i>♪ Try to wake up, ahh ♪</i>

23:22.176 --> 23:26.143
<i>♪ Cannibal class, killin' the son, ahh ♪</i>

23:26.143 --> 23:28.230
<i>♪ Bury a friend ♪</i>

23:28.230 --> 23:30.443
<i>♪ I wanna end me ♪</i>
‐ [ panting ]

23:38.960 --> 23:40.881
[ car horn honking ]

23:41.924 --> 23:43.511
[ horn honking ]

23:53.405 --> 23:55.284
BIG DICK:
Matty Ross.

23:57.455 --> 23:59.752
You're like Rapunzel! I love it!

24:00.545 --> 24:02.006
‐ What are you doing?

24:02.006 --> 24:04.595
‐ Dropping off your signing bonus.

24:04.595 --> 24:06.766
Why don'tcha come down?
Take her for a spin?

24:06.766 --> 24:08.238
‐ I already said no.

24:08.238 --> 24:09.479
BIG DICK: Well,
that was to my first offer.

24:09.479 --> 24:10.690
You were smart to turn that down.

24:10.690 --> 24:13.112
You'll find a much‐improved offer
in the glove box.

24:13.112 --> 24:15.282
Think you're gonna like it.

24:15.282 --> 24:16.869
‐ Perry Walsh get one of these?

24:18.748 --> 24:21.796
‐ You know, I'd suggest
you move on with your life, Matty.

24:21.796 --> 24:25.219
What I'm doing now...
this is the easy way.

24:25.219 --> 24:27.766
You don't want to do this the hard way,
I promise.

24:28.643 --> 24:30.522
You know, a year from now
I'm gonna have

24:30.522 --> 24:33.570
eight luxury beachfront units
on this spot.

24:34.655 --> 24:36.659
That's something
you can take to the bank.

24:42.838 --> 24:45.468
‐ I don't care what you say.
It's Big Dick.

24:45.468 --> 24:47.180
VERONICA: Matty‐‐
‐ He bought me a <i>car.</i>

24:47.180 --> 24:48.348
‐ Matty...

24:48.348 --> 24:50.770
‐ I know that you're working off
some theory about nails‐‐

24:50.770 --> 24:52.566
‐ Matty!

24:52.566 --> 24:54.737
You're right.
KEITH: Yeah.

24:54.737 --> 24:57.868
We think Big Dick had Perry Walsh
plant the Sea Sprite bomb, too.

24:58.995 --> 25:01.458
‐ And Penn Epner is responsible
for the other ones.

25:01.458 --> 25:02.586
‐ We think.

25:03.546 --> 25:07.804
‐ I‐I know he's a little obnoxious,
but he's nice enough.

25:07.804 --> 25:10.017
Why would he want
to kill all those people?

25:10.017 --> 25:14.275
‐ Pfft. Feel important? I‐‐
We're still drilling down on motive.

25:14.275 --> 25:16.196
‐ Which is why Big Dick
is easier to prove.

25:16.196 --> 25:18.701
We just need something
that connects him to Perry Walsh.

25:18.701 --> 25:19.118
[ phone ringing ]

25:19.118 --> 25:21.122
VERONICA: Financial payments,
phone records...

25:22.918 --> 25:23.586
<i>[ beep ]</i>

25:23.586 --> 25:25.214
‐ Mars Investigations.

25:26.424 --> 25:28.220
Jesus.

25:28.220 --> 25:29.389
Hold on.

25:31.519 --> 25:32.938
Okay.

25:32.938 --> 25:35.484
[ muttering ]

25:35.484 --> 25:37.488
What was‐‐ What was that last part?

25:40.996 --> 25:43.375
'Kay. Yeah.
Okay, got it.

25:43.375 --> 25:45.672
We'll be right there. All right. Bye.

25:46.841 --> 25:49.220
The bomber sent a limerick
to the police

25:49.220 --> 25:52.644
promising bomb number six
in the next 72 hours.

25:52.644 --> 25:55.316
<i>Now</i> Marcia wants to hear
our Penn theory.

25:55.316 --> 25:56.527
‐ A limerick?

25:56.527 --> 25:57.738
KEITH:
Hold on.

25:58.865 --> 26:00.785
"Three laps 'round the sun,
I'll be gloating

26:00.785 --> 26:03.457
About more beautiful bodies exploding

26:03.457 --> 26:05.002
Their flesh we will squeegee

26:05.002 --> 26:06.964
At midday 'round Fiji

26:06.964 --> 26:09.511
Plus the heroes upon whom we're doting"

26:16.609 --> 26:18.278
‐ Well, what about Big Dick?

26:18.278 --> 26:20.115
‐ We'll get to him, I promise.

26:20.115 --> 26:22.078
But there's a ticking clock
on this one.

26:22.078 --> 26:24.499
‐ Is it okay if I hang out
and charge my cell?

26:24.499 --> 26:26.461
I can just answer the phone and whatnot.

26:26.461 --> 26:28.966
‐ Yeah, just don't do anything
I wouldn't do.

26:28.966 --> 26:31.262
‐ And most of the things
that she <i>would</i> do.

26:31.262 --> 26:32.683
‐ Thanks.

26:36.565 --> 26:39.028
‐ Well, the shit
has officially hit the fan.

26:39.028 --> 26:41.491
‐ Well, if Marcia's calling us down,
it certainly has.

26:42.703 --> 26:44.038
‐ My boss is joining.

26:44.038 --> 26:46.042
KEITH:
All the way in from Virginia?

26:46.042 --> 26:48.463
‐ Not exactly.

26:48.463 --> 26:50.300
MAN [ on speakerphone ]:
<i>The pizza guy?!</i>

26:50.300 --> 26:51.804
<i>You're tellin' me the shmo</i>

26:51.804 --> 26:54.727
<i>popping up on the news</i>
<i>with the crazy theories is our guy?</i>

26:54.727 --> 26:56.396
‐ We're saying we have a theory

26:56.396 --> 26:59.152
that supports the idea of Mr. Epner
as the bomber.

26:59.152 --> 27:01.741
The nails that we found‐‐
MAN: <i>I heard you the first time.</i>

27:01.741 --> 27:03.076
<i>Does pizza guy have a criminal record?</i>

27:03.076 --> 27:04.705
‐ No.

27:04.705 --> 27:07.084
MAN: <i>Any explosives background?</i>
<i>Military? Mining?</i>

27:08.295 --> 27:10.007
‐ None that we know of.

27:10.007 --> 27:11.594
MAN: <i>Booker, D'Amato, you there?</i>

27:11.594 --> 27:13.806
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Yes, sir.

27:13.806 --> 27:15.142
MAN: <i>This is nothing.</i>

27:15.142 --> 27:18.649
<i>I want you to go pick up Lassiter in L. A.</i>
<i>He's gotta be the guy.</i>

27:19.275 --> 27:20.862
‐ Okay, sir.

27:20.862 --> 27:21.947
MAN: <i>Thanks, everyone.</i>

27:21.947 --> 27:24.578
<i>This has been entertaining</i>
<i>if nothing else.</i>

27:24.578 --> 27:25.705
<i>[ click ]</i>

27:26.331 --> 27:27.834
<i>[ beep ]</i>

27:29.588 --> 27:31.800
‐ Okay, uh, I guess
we're hittin' the road

27:31.800 --> 27:33.094
to go pick up the guy

27:33.094 --> 27:35.517
that nobody in this room
believes is guilty.

27:38.188 --> 27:40.108
‐ Let's go, honey.

27:40.108 --> 27:42.739
‐ Hey. About that limerick.

27:42.739 --> 27:46.747
Fiji Sandwich World on the boardwalk,
it's a couple of blocks from my place.

27:46.747 --> 27:49.586
I think that might be the target.
"Heroes" are sometimes sandwiches‐‐

27:49.586 --> 27:52.258
‐ Yeah, no shit.
We're way ahead of you.

27:52.258 --> 27:54.387
We've already notified the shop,

27:54.387 --> 27:57.142
and we will be evacuating
a two‐block radius.

27:57.142 --> 27:59.565
We've also got bomb‐sniffing dogs
on the way.

28:00.440 --> 28:01.944
VERONICA: Okay.
KEITH: All right.

28:01.944 --> 28:03.446
‐ Uh, hey, Mars.

28:06.244 --> 28:09.333
I think there's something
to your nail theory.

28:09.333 --> 28:13.091
Plus, I <i>really</i> wanna show up the FBI.

28:13.926 --> 28:17.099
MAN [ on TV ]
<i>All righty! It's fun time, America.</i>

28:17.099 --> 28:20.523
<i>Put the cares of the day behind you.</i>
<i>It's time for fun!</i>

28:20.523 --> 28:25.115
‐ Neptune spring break
is honestly worse than Fyre Festival.

28:25.115 --> 28:27.662
‐ One thousand percent.

28:27.662 --> 28:30.417
‐ At least the shrooms
are starting to kick in.

28:30.417 --> 28:33.089
‐ Yeah.
‐ Are you seeing these lights?

28:33.089 --> 28:34.551
‐ <i>So, what's going on, Zorak?</i>

28:34.551 --> 28:36.555
‐ They're so c‐‐ Huh?!

28:36.555 --> 28:38.611
OFFICER 1: Freeze! Police!
Let's see your hands!

28:38.611 --> 28:39.645
OFFICER 2: Hands up!

28:39.645 --> 28:42.149
OFFICER 3: Don't move!
MARCIA: Where's Penn Epner?

28:42.149 --> 28:43.944
GUY: Who?
‐ He owns this place.

28:43.944 --> 28:45.740
‐ Well, he's got an apartment
in the basement.

28:45.740 --> 28:46.909
‐ Basement. Go!

28:46.909 --> 28:48.579
This is what I need you to do.

28:48.579 --> 28:51.292
I need you to call Carl,
I need you to check the perimeter.

28:51.292 --> 28:54.006
‐ The guys upstairs said they saw him
leaving, carrying a bag, last night.

28:54.006 --> 28:56.219
OFFICER 4:
Chief, look at this.

28:56.219 --> 28:57.806
Printouts from the internet.

28:57.806 --> 29:00.520
How‐to's for every kind of explosive
our bomber has used.

29:08.034 --> 29:10.205
‐ Put out an APB for Penn Epner.

29:15.340 --> 29:17.971
‐ So, like, eggs are zero points...
‐ Uh‐huh.

29:17.971 --> 29:22.187
‐ ...beans, chicken‐‐
but you gotta take the skin off‐‐

29:22.187 --> 29:24.943
‐ Are you kidding me with this shit?

29:24.943 --> 29:27.866
This is basically just you callin' me fat.

29:27.866 --> 29:30.872
‐ I'm just sayin',
my ma eats all day‐‐

29:30.872 --> 29:34.420
like, <i>all</i> day‐‐
and she's down 15 pounds.

29:34.420 --> 29:35.548
‐ Good for her.

29:37.384 --> 29:39.221
‐ My man.

29:39.221 --> 29:40.600
I saw on the news‐‐

29:40.600 --> 29:43.647
that Mexican kid
who died at the Sea Sprite,

29:43.647 --> 29:45.693
guess who his uncle is.

29:45.693 --> 29:47.070
‐ Guillermo del Toro.

29:47.070 --> 29:48.616
‐ El Despiadado.

29:50.494 --> 29:52.832
That's who your sister's boyfriend
is working for, right?

29:55.922 --> 29:58.886
‐ Yeah.
‐ Makes you think, doesn't it?

29:58.886 --> 30:00.556
What do you suppose he's doing here?

30:06.025 --> 30:09.490
‐ [ Veronica tapping on keyboard ]
‐ [ Keith chuckling ]

30:11.327 --> 30:13.206
KEITH: All right, thanks.
Thanks for the heads‐up.

30:13.206 --> 30:14.333
Bye‐bye.
[ hangs up phone ]

30:14.333 --> 30:16.755
‐ Who you been talkin' to?
KEITH: Cliff.

30:16.755 --> 30:20.638
He was at the police station.
There's an APB for our pizza guy.

30:21.389 --> 30:23.393
Cliff heard that he wasn't at his place

30:23.393 --> 30:26.274
and word is,
he asked for time off at Cho's.

30:26.274 --> 30:27.735
The guy's in the wind.

30:27.735 --> 30:30.992
But with a $250,000 reward
for his capture,

30:30.992 --> 30:32.494
someone's gonna find him.

30:32.494 --> 30:34.791
‐ And that someone's gonna be us.

30:34.791 --> 30:36.002
‐ Pardon?

30:37.004 --> 30:39.091
‐ When I want to their meeting,
I got the impression

30:39.091 --> 30:42.389
that Penn was more than friends
with one of his Murderheads.

30:42.389 --> 30:46.355
I only knew her first name, Carol,
<i>but</i> she's a librarian at Hearst.

30:46.355 --> 30:47.984
‐ Your old employer.

30:47.984 --> 30:51.115
‐ Long story short,
Carol called in sick yesterday,

30:51.115 --> 30:54.915
and Carol owns a cabin
just outside Mesa Grande.

30:54.915 --> 30:56.752
‐ Hot damn!

30:56.752 --> 30:58.881
‐ Get strapped, old timer.

30:58.881 --> 31:01.720
We are gonna go capture
one of America's most wanted.

31:05.185 --> 31:08.024
‐ Are you kidding me
with this car, man?

31:08.024 --> 31:09.360
‐ '66.

31:09.360 --> 31:11.990
Mint condition, original leather,

31:11.990 --> 31:14.328
original wood grain on the dash.

31:15.121 --> 31:18.587
Bought this from a little old lady
who kept it covered in a garage.

31:18.587 --> 31:21.175
‐ Ahh.
‐ It's got 23,000 miles on it.

31:21.175 --> 31:22.260
‐ Beautiful.

31:23.221 --> 31:24.306
Hey, Clyde,

31:24.306 --> 31:27.187
you know anything about these two guys
up from Mexico?

31:27.187 --> 31:30.569
They work for a cartel boss. He lost
his nephew in the Sea Sprite bombing?

31:31.362 --> 31:32.740
‐ No.

31:32.740 --> 31:35.955
But I don't really have my finger on
the pulse of the Mexican underworld.

31:37.332 --> 31:40.338
‐ I thought you knew everyone
who's ever served time, Clyde.

31:42.175 --> 31:46.308
It could mean trouble for whoever's
responsible for that Sea Sprite bomb.

31:47.227 --> 31:48.981
‐ I heard that was Perry Walsh,

31:48.981 --> 31:51.778
and that guy's already
blown himself up, so...

31:52.697 --> 31:54.116
‐ Hm. Huh.

31:54.951 --> 31:57.874
I wonder what those two guys
are still doin' up here, then.

32:02.132 --> 32:03.342
Oh. Thanks.

32:03.342 --> 32:06.390
My guys have been on my ass all week
about gettin' paid.

32:08.394 --> 32:10.065
‐ Well, that's the last of it,

32:10.065 --> 32:13.112
so, uh, you might want
to remind them about rainy days.

32:14.741 --> 32:15.951
‐ Job's done?

32:16.995 --> 32:18.665
‐ Yeah. Spring break's over.

32:18.665 --> 32:21.212
‐ Not for four days, it isn't.

32:21.212 --> 32:24.259
Clyde, look,
there's gotta be more you need, right?

32:24.259 --> 32:27.725
I mean, I got a lot of people
countin' on this. On <i>me.</i>

32:28.685 --> 32:31.107
‐ Good thing you're
an enterprising kinda guy.

32:31.107 --> 32:33.194
I'm sure you'll find other ways
to make money.

32:40.083 --> 32:41.628
[ engine starts ]

32:42.295 --> 32:44.091
<i>[ phone buzzing ]</i>
‐ This guy's been blowing up your phone.

32:44.091 --> 32:47.347
I think he's got tires for you
or some... thing.

32:47.347 --> 32:48.224
What's wrong with you?

32:48.224 --> 32:50.395
‐ Veronica Mars.

32:50.395 --> 32:52.775
The "I told you so"
I'm gonna be hearin' from her.

32:52.775 --> 32:55.029
‐ Well, you don't have to worry
about her much longer.

32:56.407 --> 32:57.827
‐ What's that supposed to mean?

32:57.827 --> 33:01.500
‐ Nothing. I'm just agreeing with you.

33:01.500 --> 33:02.879
She's annoying.

33:02.879 --> 33:04.214
‐ Claudia.

33:04.214 --> 33:06.051
Do not lie to me.

33:06.051 --> 33:08.765
Why am I not gonna
have to worry about Veronica?

33:09.976 --> 33:12.690
<i>[ music playing ]</i>

33:19.119 --> 33:22.543
SINGER:
<i>♪ You're tall, dark and handsome ♪</i>

33:22.543 --> 33:24.964
‐ I'll be right back. Don't go anywhere.
SINGER: <i>♪ Charming and then some ♪</i>

33:24.964 --> 33:26.676
‐ Oh, I got no plans.
‐ [ chuckles ]

33:26.676 --> 33:29.431
SINGER:
<i>♪ Know how to romance 'em ♪</i>

33:30.684 --> 33:33.774
<i>♪ I see through it all ♪</i>
‐ I'm‐‐ I'm just getting some wood.

33:33.774 --> 33:36.988
Some firewood for the... fireplace.
SINGER: <i>♪ You do everything too fast ♪</i>

33:36.988 --> 33:38.324
‐ [ whispers ] God.

33:38.324 --> 33:41.413
SINGER:
<i>♪ You move like a whiplash... ♪</i>

33:44.086 --> 33:45.046
[ guns cock ]

33:45.046 --> 33:46.675
Jesus! What the hell!

33:46.675 --> 33:48.720
‐ There's an APB out for you.

33:48.720 --> 33:52.603
Haven't you heard? <i>You're</i> the bomber
everyone's looking for.

33:52.603 --> 33:56.402
‐ I‐I was almost killed
in the Sea Sprite bombing!

33:56.402 --> 33:57.697
I got hit with shrapnel!

33:57.697 --> 34:00.869
‐ You got hit with a nail
from a piece of string art

34:00.869 --> 34:02.707
in the lobby.
‐ What?

34:02.707 --> 34:04.919
‐ But since you thought
it was bomb shrapnel,

34:04.919 --> 34:07.758
you put the same nails
in all your copycat bombs,

34:07.758 --> 34:08.719
didn't you, Penn?

34:08.719 --> 34:10.221
‐ I‐I'm going to call‐‐

34:10.221 --> 34:13.185
I‐‐ I am calling my attorney!

34:13.185 --> 34:14.689
Oh‐‐ Oh, God.

34:14.689 --> 34:15.398
[ gunfire ]

34:15.398 --> 34:15.983
Oh, Jesus!

34:15.983 --> 34:19.114
KEITH:
Inside! Get inside! Get inside!

34:22.872 --> 34:25.460
[ gunfire continues ]

34:27.172 --> 34:28.842
‐ [ panting ]

34:33.518 --> 34:36.566
[ gunfire ]

34:39.071 --> 34:40.783
‐ How'd you miss that shot?

34:40.783 --> 34:41.993
‐ Shut up.

34:48.130 --> 34:50.761
CAROL:
[ screams ] Who's shooting?!

34:50.761 --> 34:53.558
VERONICA:
Get in there and don't come out!

34:53.558 --> 34:54.602
[ gunfire ]

34:54.602 --> 34:55.687
KEITH: Ohh.

34:55.687 --> 34:56.815
DODIE:
Send him out!

34:56.815 --> 34:59.570
‐ I've got nine bullets left.
How 'bout you?

35:00.948 --> 35:03.119
DODIE: Let's split up!
‐ Dad?

35:03.119 --> 35:05.164
‐ I forgot.

35:05.164 --> 35:08.755
I left my ammo in the glove box.
I forgot to load my gun.

35:08.755 --> 35:10.133
DODIE:
Go around back!

35:11.301 --> 35:14.266
‐ Okay. Uh, take this.

35:14.266 --> 35:16.521
I'll run and get it.
‐ No. No, goddamnit, Veronica.

35:16.521 --> 35:18.274
That's‐‐ That's suicide.
‐ I will be quick.

35:18.274 --> 35:19.192
DODIE:
Cover me!

35:22.575 --> 35:23.702
‐ Okay.

35:24.579 --> 35:25.748
Six.

35:30.632 --> 35:32.845
No. No, no. You stupid shit.

35:39.817 --> 35:41.946
[ gunfire ]

35:41.946 --> 35:44.786
DODIE: He's in the car!
‐ Three.

35:46.330 --> 35:47.625
[ gunfire ]

35:56.768 --> 35:58.270
VERONICA:
Hurry, Dad. <i>Hurry!</i>

35:58.270 --> 35:59.231
[ gunshot ]

36:01.694 --> 36:03.280
DODIE:
Over there!

36:03.280 --> 36:06.495
‐ [ panting ]

36:09.209 --> 36:10.963
‐ [ muttering ]

36:19.396 --> 36:22.528
[ vehicles approaching ]

36:26.493 --> 36:27.997
DODIE:
The hell is that?

36:30.459 --> 36:32.506
[ motorcycles revving engines ]

36:37.348 --> 36:38.475
WEEVIL:
Head on out, boys!

36:38.475 --> 36:40.564
No one's touchin' her!

36:41.440 --> 36:42.693
Head home!

36:48.622 --> 36:52.086
[ motorcycles departing ]

37:05.279 --> 37:07.408
[ Weevil starts motorcycle ]

37:14.422 --> 37:16.970
[ roar of motorcycle fading ]

37:29.829 --> 37:34.295
‐ This is a flagrant waste
of taxpayer dollars.

37:34.295 --> 37:37.343
I am not a bomber!
‐ Save it for the cameras.

37:37.343 --> 37:39.724
Hey, Mars. Don't go anywhere.

37:39.724 --> 37:42.688
I'll get a statement from you and your dad
when I'm through with him.

37:42.688 --> 37:43.940
C'mon, let's go. C'mon.

37:48.700 --> 37:49.910
‐ Veronica.

37:53.208 --> 37:54.044
How ya doin'?

37:54.044 --> 37:55.714
‐ Okay.

37:55.714 --> 37:58.135
I'm still pretty jacked up on adrenaline.

37:58.135 --> 37:59.764
LEO: Yeah. I heard.

38:00.932 --> 38:02.143
‐ [ no audible dialogue ]

38:02.143 --> 38:04.899
‐ Learned a lot about Mr. Epner
since yesterday.

38:04.899 --> 38:06.485
‐ Yeah?
‐ Yeah.

38:06.485 --> 38:08.865
At 18, he lands in Neptune
to go to Hearst,

38:08.865 --> 38:11.829
starts playin' "Assassination"‐‐
remember that bein' the thing?

38:11.829 --> 38:14.710
‐ Yeah, a bunch of dildo college boys

38:14.710 --> 38:17.883
shooting each other with paint pellets
until only one dildo survives.

38:17.883 --> 38:21.056
‐ Only Penn took the game
a little bit too far.

38:21.056 --> 38:23.435
Always had to be number one
on the kill list.

38:23.435 --> 38:25.857
Shot a classmate
while he was taking an exam.

38:25.857 --> 38:28.237
Kid lost his eye.
‐ Damn, Penn.

38:28.237 --> 38:29.573
‐ So he gets kicked out of Hearst,

38:29.573 --> 38:32.411
and at his expulsion hearing
they ask him was it worth it,

38:32.411 --> 38:35.167
you know, gettin' kicked out,
failing all your classes,

38:35.167 --> 38:37.046
taking out a friend's eye.

38:37.046 --> 38:40.427
He answers,
"Well, I won, didn't I?"

38:40.427 --> 38:42.140
Spends the last two decades

38:42.140 --> 38:44.144
deliverin' pizzas
and living with his grandmother.

38:44.144 --> 38:45.814
She left him the house
after she passed.

38:47.108 --> 38:50.489
Phone records show
he's been talkin' to publicists.

38:50.489 --> 38:52.870
[scoffs]
Thinks he's gettin' a book deal.

38:53.872 --> 38:55.124
‐ Hm.

38:56.711 --> 38:58.548
When do you head back?

38:58.548 --> 39:00.677
‐ Tomorrow morning.

39:00.677 --> 39:03.223
‐ Oh, wow. That's fast.

39:03.223 --> 39:04.852
‐ Yeah. Uh,

39:04.852 --> 39:07.900
FBI will send out an interrogator
to work on Penn in the morning.

39:07.900 --> 39:11.616
We still gotta figure out if this bomb's
gonna go off 36 hours from now.

39:11.616 --> 39:14.245
I'll head back to Virginia
for a couple days, and...

39:14.245 --> 39:16.542
then, you know, on to the next.

39:19.464 --> 39:20.759
I'm sorry.

39:20.759 --> 39:24.265
I shouldn't have invited myself over
the other day.

39:24.265 --> 39:25.936
That was wrong of me.

39:25.936 --> 39:29.150
‐ Oh, that?
It... didn't even cross my mind.

39:29.150 --> 39:30.820
‐ [ laughs softly ]

39:30.820 --> 39:32.991
‐ It's been good seeing you, Leo.

39:35.664 --> 39:36.749
‐ You too, Ms. Mars.

39:46.727 --> 39:48.355
VERONICA:
You all right?

39:48.355 --> 39:50.025
‐ Not really.

39:51.069 --> 39:52.363
I screwed up.

39:52.363 --> 39:54.409
My screwed‐up brain
almost got us killed.

39:54.409 --> 39:55.745
‐ But it didn't.

39:55.745 --> 39:57.958
‐ I could have gotten you killed.

40:00.087 --> 40:02.341
‐ Dad, I forget shit all the time.

40:02.341 --> 40:04.178
‐ No. Veronica, no,
we're not gonna pretend

40:04.178 --> 40:06.182
that this was a one‐off
or no big deal.

40:07.059 --> 40:08.980
‐ Dad‐‐
‐ I'm sorry, honey.

40:11.067 --> 40:12.278
I'm done.

40:16.662 --> 40:18.750
C‐Can you give me a minute here?

40:18.750 --> 40:21.797
I'm just gonna dull my pain
with a fried fruit pie,

40:21.797 --> 40:25.764
and you watching me eat it
is gonna take all the joy out of it.

40:25.764 --> 40:29.103
‐ You're not done. It was one bad‐‐
KEITH: Veronica.

40:31.149 --> 40:33.070
[ voice breaking ] Please.

40:56.617 --> 40:57.994
[ Pony whining ]

40:57.994 --> 40:59.247
‐ Hey there, Pony.

41:00.124 --> 41:01.877
Hey.

41:01.877 --> 41:03.088
[ kisses ] Hi.

41:03.088 --> 41:05.134
LOGAN: Hey.

41:05.134 --> 41:09.475
Notice any international hot spots
back to room temperature? That was <i>me.</i>

41:09.475 --> 41:11.689
‐ You're home.
LOGAN: Yeah.

41:18.870 --> 41:21.207
Are you okay?

41:21.207 --> 41:22.752
‐ I am now.

41:43.711 --> 41:45.214
You still have that ring?

41:49.138 --> 41:50.558
LOGAN:
I do.

41:52.521 --> 41:55.025
‐ Well, look at that.
You already know your lines.

41:58.908 --> 42:00.537
LOGAN:
Why now?

42:00.537 --> 42:02.791
‐ I had a moment of clarity.

42:05.588 --> 42:09.303
VERONICA: <i>When I woke up</i>
<i>after my Leo sex dream,</i>

42:09.303 --> 42:11.559
<i>all I felt was relief.</i>

42:12.476 --> 42:15.984
<i>Relief that I hadn't done anything</i>
<i>to hurt Logan.</i>

42:15.984 --> 42:19.741
<i>And a few hours later, when I thought,</i>
<i>"I'm going to die tonight,"</i>

42:19.741 --> 42:22.664
<i>the only person I thought about</i>
<i>was Logan.</i>

42:30.178 --> 42:32.601
‐ There's the man of the hour.

42:32.601 --> 42:36.065
Heard the news,
thought it called for a ten‐year rye.

42:39.405 --> 42:41.535
You caught the bad guy...

42:41.535 --> 42:44.916
made 250 large doin' it...

42:44.916 --> 42:46.795
and...

42:46.795 --> 42:49.050
it's that little shit Penn Epner.

42:49.050 --> 42:51.012
[ laughs ]

42:51.012 --> 42:53.768
What's it like up there on cloud nine?

42:53.768 --> 42:56.815
‐ You think I'm on cloud nine?

42:56.815 --> 42:59.445
This case almost got my daughter killed.

42:59.445 --> 43:01.449
Almost got me killed.

43:01.449 --> 43:04.455
If not for your employee Weevil,
we <i>would</i> be dead.

43:05.499 --> 43:08.171
‐ I'm‐‐ I'm sorry, what's a Weevil?

43:08.171 --> 43:09.966
‐ Stop.

43:09.966 --> 43:13.348
This game we've been playing is over.

43:17.398 --> 43:19.193
‐ I'm sorry, Keith.

43:20.780 --> 43:22.867
I thought you'd be on top of the world.

43:24.078 --> 43:26.249
You got your guy.

43:26.249 --> 43:29.338
I mean, let's take our happiness
where we find it.

43:29.338 --> 43:32.094
‐ Penn Epner didn't bomb the Sea Sprite.

43:32.094 --> 43:34.473
He didn't bomb Perry Walsh's house,
either.

43:34.473 --> 43:37.772
I'm 99% sure Big Dick
was responsible for the Sea Sprite,

43:37.772 --> 43:40.026
and when we get him on this,
my final case,

43:40.026 --> 43:43.951
I suspect we'll find out
what your involvement, if any, was.

43:43.951 --> 43:47.166
How well do you suppose Big Dick
will stand up to interrogation?

43:47.166 --> 43:51.215
The over‐under must be...
three minutes...

43:51.215 --> 43:53.052
before he starts naming names.

43:57.562 --> 43:59.023
‐ Here's to you, Keith.

44:04.576 --> 44:06.454
You're a good man.

44:08.041 --> 44:10.212
Consider me in your corner.

44:11.172 --> 44:13.009
That is...

44:13.009 --> 44:15.180
unless you're goin' against me.

44:17.977 --> 44:19.146
To the good times.

44:40.606 --> 44:42.234
<i>[ line out ringing ]</i>

44:42.234 --> 44:43.863
<i>[ ringing ]</i>

44:43.863 --> 44:47.244
‐ What's up?
You got more work for me?

44:48.288 --> 44:50.292
‐ Need you to arrange a meeting.

44:55.051 --> 44:57.385
Gentlemen.

44:57.385 --> 44:58.851
I have a little gift.

44:59.519 --> 45:01.648
I understand you're interested
in finding the scumbag

45:01.648 --> 45:04.069
responsible for bombing the Sea Sprite.

45:04.069 --> 45:05.196
‐ Maybe.

45:08.954 --> 45:10.123
CLYDE:
Enjoy.

45:13.923 --> 45:16.177
BIG DICK [ on recording ]:
<i>Set up a trust fund for P. W.'s kid.</i>

45:16.177 --> 45:18.974
<i>Use a Cayman account.</i>
<i>Enough to cover college.</i>

45:21.980 --> 45:24.485
‐ Hey, if you woulda supported the plan
in the first place

45:24.485 --> 45:26.030
it wouldn't have gone off the rails,

45:26.030 --> 45:28.911
and I never would have had to ask
Perry Walsh to do what he does.

45:29.704 --> 45:31.959
‐ Or you could've offered Ross
another million.

45:31.959 --> 45:33.629
He woulda sold you the Sea Sprite.

45:33.629 --> 45:35.967
And those four people
would still be alive.

45:35.967 --> 45:38.681
‐ Yeah, well, that would have
been overpaying, and I never overpay.

45:45.318 --> 45:48.491
MARCIA: We found stacks
of bomb‐making materials

45:48.491 --> 45:49.326
at your home.

45:49.326 --> 45:52.959
PENN: Marcia‐‐
‐ Chief Langdon, asshole.

45:52.959 --> 45:55.548
‐ [ scoffs ] How many times
do I have to tell you?

45:55.548 --> 45:58.887
I am part of a group that
researches unsolved crimes!

45:58.887 --> 46:01.560
What you found was research!

46:01.560 --> 46:04.733
‐ You are not climbing
out of this hole.

46:04.733 --> 46:06.945
This is your grave.

46:06.945 --> 46:09.784
So you tell me right now
where that bomb is,

46:09.784 --> 46:13.374
or I will start packing the earth in
so thick over your head,

46:13.374 --> 46:15.755
you will forget the taste of air!

46:15.755 --> 46:18.301
‐ Oh, there he is! I kept your card.

46:18.301 --> 46:19.679
‐ Oh, goody.

46:19.679 --> 46:23.061
Chief Langdon. Can I speak
with my client alone, please?

46:26.735 --> 46:27.820
‐ [ sighs ]

46:37.422 --> 46:40.136
‐ She is gonna regret
all this bad cop posturing

46:40.136 --> 46:41.848
when she reads my memoir.

46:41.848 --> 46:45.773
‐ I would keep those and any
other thoughts you have to yourself.

46:45.773 --> 46:49.823
You're gonna get out tomorrow if they
don't have enough to arrest you with,

46:49.823 --> 46:50.908
